  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a lived reality for many of us in the field. Growing up in a household where both parents held PhDs, I was exposed to the idea that intelligence and aptitude are fixed traits from an early age. This mindset, unfortunately, is deeply embedded in how we view success in technical fields. When I first started my engineering career, I noticed how the constant pressure to prove oneself in a space where stereotypes about gender, race, and ability often dominate can be exhausting. For example, during a recent project with my team, a junior colleague—a woman of color—expressed hesitation about contributing because she feared her ideas wouldn't be taken seriously. This isn't just about individual anxiety; it's a systemic issue that undermines the very diversity we need to innovate. Addressing stereotype threat requires more than just awareness. It starts with creating environments where everyone feels safe to make mistakes and where contributions are valued regardless of background. As a creative engineer who values collaboration, I've seen firsthand how small changes—like structured mentorship programs, inclusive language training, and transparent feedback loops—can shift the culture. But it's not enough to just talk about it; we need to actively dismantle the biases that stem from stereotypes. In my daily life, I try to model vulnerability by admitting my own uncertainties and encouraging others to do the same. This approach aligns with my high openness to new ideas and my moderate conscientiousness, which drives me to be methodical in addressing these issues. Ultimately, if we want STEM to reflect the diversity of our society, we must confront stereotype threat head-on, not as a problem to be solved in isolation, but as part of a broader effort to build equitable and innovative systems.",
